    "summary": "The Battle of Granicus (334 BC) was the first major engagement of [[event:75|Alexander the Great's Empire]]'s campaign against the Persian Achaemenid Empire, fought at the Granicus River in northwestern Anatolia. Alexander crossed into Asia with roughly 40,000 troops and immediately faced the Persian provincial forces drawn up on the far bank of the river.\n\nAlexander's generals urged caution — the crossing was difficult and the Persian cavalry held a strong defensive position on the far bank. Alexander reportedly dismissed these objections and led the Companion cavalry across the river directly against the Persian line, personally engaging in hand-to-hand combat and nearly being killed when a Persian nobleman struck him from behind with an axe, saved by the intervention of his bodyguard Cleitus the Black. The Persian cavalry was routed, and the Greek mercenary infantry, who had constituted the most professional Persian force, were surrounded and largely massacred — Alexander refused to grant them quarter for fighting against Greeks in Persian service. The victory opened Anatolia to Alexander's advance and demonstrated his aggressive personal style of leadership that would define the entire campaign.",
